             For atomic electrons some properties are constants of nature, some definite and some indefinite.
             Atomic electrons do not have a definite location, velocity or trajectory.


             <h3>Electronic Constants of Nature:</h3>
            For all electrons always, these are constants:
            <ul>
                <li>The electron mass: 9.109 x 10^-31 kg</li>	
                <li>Electric charge: -1.602 x 10^-19 C</li>
                <li>Magnitude of spin: 1/2</li>
                <li>Magnetic moment: âˆ’1.001 u_B</li> 	 
            </ul>

            <h3>Definite for atomic electrons (assuming no transition):</h3>
            <ul>
                <li>the number of electrons, (e.g. 92 for Uranium atom)</li>   
                <li>the energy of each electron (different electrons have different energies)</li> 
            </ul>

            <h3>Indefinite for atomic electrons: </h3>
            <ul>
                <li>the location of an electron</li>
                <li>the linear momentum of an electron</li>
                <li>the three components of spin</li> 
            </ul>
 
